   =============================================================================
   This is a very short manual about nano-archimedes
   =============================================================================

   nano-archimedes is a quantum mechanical simulator
   which implements the single- and many-body signed particle formulation of
   quantum mechanics, which discretization is also know as the signed particle
   Wigner Monte Carlo method. The signed particle formulation of
   quantum mechanics is an alternative model which describes quantum systems
   in terms of ensemble of signed particles which, in turn, are able to fully
   reconstruct the corresponding Wigner quasi-distribution functions.
   This theory is, of course, completely equivalent to more standard
   formulations such as the Schroedinger model.

   For more information, lectures and results about the Wigner formalism,
   please visit the following website:

   www.nano-archimedes.com


   In this release, nano-archimedes simulates a Gaussian wave-packet going towards
   a potential barrier.

   The parameters defining the problem can be found in the file nano-archimedes.c,
   where:

   - MSTAR                  = effective mass
   - INUM                   = initial maximum number of particle per phase-space cell
   - LX                     = length of the X-spatial domain
   - LY                     = length of the Y-spatial domain (only in 2D)
   - LC                     = length defining the momentum discretization
                              (sometimes referred to as "coherence lenght" or "cut-off length")
   - NX                     = number of cells in x-direction
   - NY                     = number of cells in y-direction (only in 2D)
   - DT                     = time step
   - ITMAX                  = total number of time steps
   - SIGMA_WAVE_PACKET      = wave packet dispersion
   - X0_WAVE_PACKET         = wave packet initial x-position
   - Y0_WAVE_PACKET         = wave packet initial y-position
   - BARRIER_POTENTIAL      = value of the potential barrier
   - BARRIER_POSITION       = barrier center position
   - BARRIER_WIDTH          = barrier width
   - K0_WAVE_PACKET         = wave packet initial wave vector
   - ANNIHILATION_FREQUENCY = number of time steps at which annihilation occurs


   ===> You can extend easily this code to more general situations by following
        the details presented in these papers:

        J.M. Sellier,
        A signed particle formulation of non-relativistic quantum mechanics,
        Journal of Computational Phyisics (2015).

        J.M. Sellier, M. Nedjalkov, I. Dimov,
        An introduction to applied quantum mechanics in the Wigner Monte Carlo formalism,
        Physics Reports 577, pp. 1-34, (2015).

   =============================================================================
   If you use nano-archimedes in your research please consider citing one of the
   papers above.
   =============================================================================

